solutions.content:
why it works without explicitly saving the state of the visited array?


When we backtrack and return from a recursive call, we reset ```_ visited[curr] to false _``` which means that the state of visited is restored to what it was before the recursive call.

The memoization table dp is used to store and retrieve previously computed results for specific combinations of curr and index. This allows the algorithm to avoid redundant calculations and significantly improves its efficiency.

In summary, while the visited array is modified during the recursion, it is effectively reset to its original state when backtracking,``` _ thanks to the visited[curr] = false statement _ ``` 
The state of visited is managed correctly within the recursive calls, and the memoization table dp ensures that previously computed results are reused to avoid unnecessary computations. This is why the algorithm works correctly without explicitly saving the state of the visited array.

```
class Solution {
public:
    string s="";
    int n;
    int dp[203][203];
    int m=1e9+7;
    int solve(int idx,int prev, vector<int>&vis)
    {
        if(idx==n) return 1;        
        if(dp[idx+1][prev+1]!=-1) return dp[idx+1][prev+1];
        long long ans=0;
        if(idx==-1)
        {
            for(int i=0; i<=n; i++) 
            {
                vis[i]=1;
                ans+=solve(0,i,vis)%m;
                ans%=m;
                vis[i]=0;
            }
        }else
        {
            for(int i=0; i<=n; i++)
            {
                if(vis[i]==0 )
                {
                    if(s[idx]=='D' &&i<prev)
                    {
                        vis[i]=1;
