<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
- dp[j] in the i-th round memorizes the number of permutations ends with j for s[0:i].

- When s[i] is 'D', update the ndp[j] with sum(dp[j:i]), which increases each element larger than j by one in the prefix.
- When s[i] is 'I', update ndp[j] with sum(dp[0:j-1]) while keeping the prefix.
- Make use of the sum of prefix to get any sum(dp[j:i]) in $$O(1)$$



# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n^2)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: 
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
  int numPermsDISequence(string s) {
      int n=s.size(),mod=1e9+7;
      vector<int> dp{1};
      for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
          vector<int> pre{0}; //pre[i]=sum(dp[0:i-1])
          int tmp=0;
          for(auto j:dp) pre.emplace_back((j+pre.back())%mod);
          vector<int> ndp;
          if(s[i]=='D') for(int j=0;j<=i+1;j++) ndp.emplace_back(pre.back()>pre[j]?pre.back()-pre[j]:pre.back()-(pre[j]-mod)); //sum(dp[j,i])
          else for(int j=0;j<=i+1;j++) ndp.emplace_back(pre[j]); //sum(dp[0],...,dp[j-1])
          dp=ndp;
      }
      int result=0;
      for(auto i:dp)  result=(result+i)%mod;
      return result;
  }
};


```

