solutions.content:
Let `dp[i][j]` be the number of permutations that `s[i:]` could form with the first number be the `j`th smallest candidate number.

Then if `s[i] == 'D'`, because for `dp[i][j]` we already choose the `j`th smallest possible value, we can only choose the candidate numbers before `j` for the `i+1`th position. So `dp[i][j] = dp[i + 1][0] + dp[i + 1][1] + ... + dp[i + 1][j - 1]`.

The same logic applies to the case when `s[i] == 'I`. We can choose the `j + 1`th, `j + 2`th... candidate value for position `i + 1`.  Note that because `j`th value is taken, the `j + 1`th value in `i`'s candidate numbers will be the `j`th value in `i+1`'s candidate numbers. So `dp[i][j] = dp[i + 1][j] + dp[i + 1][j + 1] + ...`.

Because `dp[i][]` only depends on `dp[i + 1][]`, we can eliminate the first dimension of dp states to save some memory.
```Scala
object Solution {
  def numPermsDISequence(s: String): Int = {
    val mod = (1e9 + 7).toInt
    def add(x: Int, y: Int) = ((x + y) % mod + mod) % mod

    s.reverse.foldLeft(Vector(1)) {
      case (dp, 'D') => Vector.tabulate(dp.size + 1)(j => (0 until j).map(dp).fold(0)(add))
      case (dp, 'I') => Vector.tabulate(dp.size + 1)(j => (j until dp.size).map(dp).fold(0)(add))
      case _ => null
    }.reduce(add)
  }
}
```

