solutions.content:
The general approach would for every cell of i and j get the possible range of row and column then add all the cell. But in this case it will take very long time and can cause TLE. So we need to come up with the batter approach.

So we will use the prefix sum approach like for an example ->
1 2 3 4
4 5 6 7
8 9 8 7
this is matrix first we are going add all the elements by its row like mat[i][j] += mat[i][j-1]
1  3   6  10
4  9  15 22
8 17 25 32
then we are adding all elements as per itscolums like mat[i][j] += mat[i-1][j]
 1    3    6   10
 5   12  21  32
13  29  46  64

The Idea is, when we get a range of upper limit and lower limit then we can use this addition value so that we will not loop though again and again for every cell

##### How does it work ->
let consider this exaple
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/85b57ea3-9bb9-4566-adca-f47c1249d06d_1621608724.7525039.png)
as per some randome value lets say we need to add this rectangle then we can get the value directly which is highlighted in hexagonal cell.
So we can say
```
if(i_low <= 0 &&  j_low <= 0) result[i][j] = mat[i_up][j_up];
```
now consider this,
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/8a8f4487-6e5a-40d9-aa01-c64e3fa5dda7_1621608974.3861787.png)
if we need to add this rectangle then we can say value heighlighted in hexagonal - value highlighted in circle cause that the extra addition added in the hexagonal highlighted value.
So
```
if(i_low <= 0) result[i][j] = mat[i_up][j_up] - mat[i_up][j_low-1];
```
Now consider this,
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/c84f3378-bb83-46c4-930b-5aedef9b81ab_1621609312.8315823.png)
if we need to add this matrix then the value will be, value highlighted in hexagonal - value highlighted in circle same as previous. So,
```
if(j_low <= 0) result[i][j] = mat[i_up][j_up] - mat[i_low-1][j_up];
```
Now consider this one,
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/b2cd7180-d9cc-4863-ae89-e9901e25db6d_1621609878.505047.png)
if i_low and j_low both are not less or equal to zero then it would be like, after subtracting 2 circle values from the hexagonal value we need to add the value highlighted with star because that's the common value (intersaction part) we are subtracting towice so we need to add it again once.
```
// if i_ow and j_low are not <= 0
result[i][j] = mat[i_up][j_up] - mat[i_up][j_low-1] - mat[i_low-1][j_up] + mat[i_low-1][j_low-1];
```

and this is the total code
```
class Solution {
    public int[][] matrixBlockSum(int[][] mat, int k) {
        int n = mat.length, m = mat[0].length;
        int[][] result = new int[n][m];
        for(int i = 0 ; i < n ; i++){
            for(int j = 1 ; j < m ; j++){
                mat[i][j] += mat[i][j-1];
            }
        }
        for(int j = 0 ; j < m ; j++){
            for(int i = 1 ; i < n ; i++){
                mat[i][j] += mat[i-1][j];
            }
        }
        for(int i = 0 ; i < n ; i++){
            for(int j = 0 ; j < m ; j++){
                int i_low = i-k, i_up = i+k;
                int j_low = j-k, j_up = j+k;
				// if i_up and j_up is exceeding the range then we have to make it as the maximum possible range in the matrix.
                if(i_up >= n) i_up = n-1;
                if(j_up >= m) j_up = m-1;
                if(i_low <= 0 && j_low <= 0){
                    result[i][j] = mat[i_up][j_up];
                } else if(i_low <= 0){
                    result[i][j] = mat[i_up][j_up]-mat[i_up][j_low-1];
                } else if(j_low <= 0){
                    result[i][j] = mat[i_up][j_up]-mat[i_low-1][j_up];
                } else result[i][j] = mat[i_up][j_up]-mat[i_up][j_low-1]-
                    mat[i_low-1][j_up]+mat[i_low-1][j_low-1];
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```
