The key idea here is integrated image, a widely used technique in the field of image processing.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/xuawai/image_1582632235.png)

And the sum of a sub-matrix `S = A[1][1] + A[1][2] + A[2][1] + A[2][2]` can be calculated as `S = S1 - S2 - S3 + S4 = B[2][2]-B[2][0]-B[0][2]+B[0][0]`, which is th basis of our solution.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/xuawai/image_1582632240.png)

----

Since `(r, c)` might be an invalid position in the matrix, we expand the matrix first to save the effort dealing with boundary conditions. For more details, refer to the codes. 

```
class Solution:
    def matrixBlockSum(self, mat, K: int):
        m = len(mat)
        n = len(mat[0])

        /* expand the m*n matrix to (m+2*(K+1))*(n+2*(K+1)) matrix */
        def expand(mat, K):
            new_mat = [[0 for _ in range(n + 2 * (K + 1))] for _ in range(m + 2 * (K + 1))]
            for i in range(m):
                for j in range(n):
                    new_mat[i + K + 1][j + K + 1] = mat[i][j]
            return new_mat

        mat = expand(mat, K)
        /* compute the integrated image */
        for i in range(m + 2 * (K + 1)):
            for j in range(n + 2 * (K + 1)):
                top_v = mat[i - 1][j] if i - 1 >= 0 else 0
                left_v = mat[i][j - 1] if j - 1 >= 0 else 0
                top_left_v = mat[i - 1][j - 1] if i - 1 >= 0 and j - 1 >= 0 else 0
                mat[i][j] = mat[i][j] + top_v + left_v - top_left_v

        /* compute the sum of each sub-matrix for answer[i][j].
         No boundary conditions have to be considered since we have expanded the original matrix
		*/
        ans = [[0 for _ in range(n)] for _ in range(m)]
        for i in range(m):
            for j in range(n):
                ans[i][j] = mat[i + (K+1) + K][j + (K+1) + K] - mat[i + (K+1) + K][j]\
                            - mat[i][j + (K+1) + K] + mat[i][j]
        return ans
	```

