solutions.content:
Here is the approach:
1. Find the `k`-th node and keep a reference to it (`a`).
2. Keep going until the end of the list, but this time with two pointers (see the picture below the code).
3. Swap the values and return the original `head`.

```csharp
public class Solution
{
    public ListNode SwapNodes(ListNode head, int k)
    {
        var h = head;

        while (--k > 0) h = h.next;
        var (a, b) = (h, head);

        while (h.next != null) (h, b) = (h.next, b.next);
        (a.val, b.val) = (b.val, a.val);

        return head;
    }
}
```

About the picture: Its upper part represents the state before the second while loop. The lower part represents the state after the second while loop:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/2c5d7b4f-33f2-440d-b13e-7ae463a7e40b_1649064078.6884098.png)

See the distance between `second` and `cur`? It's `k`, so when `cur` reaches the end of the list, `second` stops at the `(end - k)`-th node. Now the values of `first` and `second` can be swapped.

