# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The solution uses two pointers, first and second, to locate the kth node from the beginning and the kth node from the end. It then swaps their values to achieve the desired result.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Initialize a dummy node and set its next pointer to the head of the linked list.
2. Initialize the first and second pointers to the dummy node.
3. Move the first pointer to the kth node from the beginning by iterating k positions.
4. Move the second pointer to the kth node from the end by iterating k positions ahead of first.
5. Swap the values of the first and second nodes.
6. Return the modified linked list.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n)

1. The solution performs two passes over the linked list:
- The first pass moves the first pointer to the kth node from the beginning.
- The second pass moves the second pointer to the kth node from the end.
2. Both passes require traversing the linked list once, resulting in a time complexity of O(n), where n is the number of nodes in the linked list.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The solution uses a constant amount of additional space to store the dummy node and the pointers.
Hence, the space complexity is O(1).

# Code
```
/**
 * Definition for singly-linked list.
 * public class ListNode {
 *     int val;
 *     ListNode next;
 *     ListNode() {}
 *     ListNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
 *     ListNode(int val, ListNode next) { this.val = val; this.next = next; }
 * }
 */
class Solution {
    public ListNode swapNodes(ListNode head, int k) {
        ListNode dummy = new ListNode(0);
        dummy.next = head;

        ListNode first = dummy;
        ListNode second = dummy;

        // Move first pointer to the kth node from the beginning
        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
            first = first.next;
        }

        // Move second pointer k positions ahead of first (kth node from the end)
        ListNode temp = first;
        while (temp != null) {
            temp = temp.next;
            second = second.next;
        }

        // Swap the values of the first and second nodes
        int tempVal = first.val;
        first.val = second.val;
        second.val = tempVal;

        return dummy.next;

    }
}
```

